Differences: Spring Data, JPA, and Hibernate

a. JPA
JPA is a specification (an interface) for object-relational mapping in Java.
It defines how Java objects are mapped to database tables, but does not provide an
implementation.

b. Hibernate
Hibernate is the most popular implementation of the JPA specification.
It provides the actual code that interacts with the database, manages the entity
lifecycle, and handles caching, lazy loading, etc.

c. Spring Data JPA
Spring Data JPA is a Spring project that builds on top of JPA.
It provides repository abstractions, query derivation, and integration with Spring,
making it easier to use JPA in Spring applications.


JPA vs Hibernate: Who Does What?

JPA:
JPA is a specification (an interface) for object-relational mapping in Java.
It defines how Java entities (classes) are mapped to database tables and how queries can be
written (using JPQL, Criteria API, etc.).
JPA does not generate SQL itself—it just defines the rules and APIs.

Hibernate:
Hibernate is an implementation of JPA.
It provides the actual code that:
Maps Java entities to database tables.
Generates SQL queries based on JPA annotations and APIs.
Executes those SQL queries against the database.
Handles features like caching, lazy loading, etc.

Query Derivation (Spring Data JPA):
Spring Data JPA adds another layer on top of JPA and Hibernate.
It allows you to write repository methods like findByName(String name).
Spring Data JPA interprets the method name, derives the query, and uses JPA (and Hibernate
underneath) to execute it.
Hibernate is the one that actually generates and runs the SQL.
